":"1223","du 1190 au 1215":"fra 1190 til 1215","Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, Frankrig","of,Roye,Somme,France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Région Parisienne, France":"Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"ABT 1185–MAY 1223":"circa 1185–mei 1223","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1182–1226":"1182–1226","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1215–1292":"1215–1292","1170–1237":"1170–1237","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1190":"1190","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","ABT 1185":"circa 1185","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1226":"1226","1214":"1214","MAY 1223":"mei 1223","1223":"1223","du 1190 au 1215":"van 1190 to 1215","Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, Frankrijk","of,Roye,Somme,France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Région Parisienne, France":"Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1185–MAY 1223":"about 1185–May 1223","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1182–1226":"1182–1226","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1215–1292":"1215–1292","1170–1237":"1170–1237","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1190":"1190","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","ABT 1185":"about 1185","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1226":"1226","1214":"1214","MAY 1223":"May 1223","1223":"1223","du 1190 au 1215":"from 1190 to 1215","Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France","of,Roye,Somme,France":"Roye, Somme, Picardie, France","Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, Région Parisienne, France":"Dammartin-en-Goële, Seine-et-Marne, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Roye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Roy   2.","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Roje</b>: from a pet form of Slavic compound personal names based on the element <i>rod</i> ‘generation, family, relatives’, e.g. <i>Rodimir</i>.","Germanized or Americanized form of Sorbian <b>Roj</b>, <b>Rój</b> or <b>Roja</b> (see   Roy   4)."],"variants":[{"name":"Roy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Normand, Andre, Jacques, Marcel, Emile, Laurent, Pierre, Cecile, Donat, Gilles.  Indian Dipak, Sumit, Amit, Ajit, Dipankar, Partha, Ranjan, Shyamal, Aloke, Amitava, Chitra, Gautam.","Scottish: nickname for a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion, from Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’. Compare   Reed  .","English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>roi</i> ‘king’, used as a nickname (see 3 below) and also as a personal name. Compare   Ray   2."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Roye was born about 1185, in Roye, Somme, Picardie, France, her father, Barthélémy de Roye, was 17 and her mother, Pétronille de Montfort, was 16. She married Raoul de Nes